description:
'''Samba de breque''' is a subgenre of [[samba]] that emerged in [[Rio de Janeiro]] between the late 1930s and early 1940s.{{sfn|Lopes|Simas|2015|p=256}}{{sfn|Marcondes|1977|p=684}}

The main characteristic of the subgenre is "breque", a Brazilian term for "[[brake]]".{{sfn|Portes|2014|p=81}} In other words, it is a samba with sudden stops, usually of a humorous character, in which the singer makes spoken comments.{{sfn|Marcondes|1977|p=684}}{{sfn|Lopes|Simas|2015|p=256}}

The singer [[Moreira da Silva]] consolidated himself as the great name of this style of samba. The first success of the subgenre was "Acertei no milhar", a samba by Wilson Batista and Geraldo Pereira.{{sfn|Tatit|2000}}{{sfn|Portes|2014|p=17}}
